ers, usually 1-2 cm in diameter, in late summer and early fall. The flowers are arranged in a capitulum, a cluster of small flowers that resemble a single bloom, and are surrounded by a ring of scales. The plant's fruit is an achene, a small, dry fruit that is 2-3 mm long and contains a single seed.", "uses": "Chrysanthemum fisherae, native to the mountainous regions of China, has been used in traditional medicine for its purported health benefits. It is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which may help to alleviate symptoms of conditions such as fever and sore throats. In addition, Chrysanthemum fisherae is thought to have antioxidant properties, which could help to protect the body from oxidative stress. The plant is also used in traditional Chinese medicine to treat a range of conditions, including digestive issues and respiratory problems. More research is needed to fully understand the medicinal properties and potential uses of Chrysanthemum fisherae.", "taxonomy": "Chrysanthemum fisherae is classified as a species of flowering plant in the family Asteraceae. It is a perennial herb that belongs to the genus Chrysanthemum. Within the Asteraceae family, Chrysanthemum fisherae is part of the tribe Anthemideae. This plant is native to the Himalayan region and is often found growing in mountainous areas. Chrysanthemum fisherae is considered an endangered species due to habitat loss and other environmental factors.", "benefits": "Chrysanthemum fisherae has been found to have potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. It has been traditionally used to treat various health conditions such as fever, rheumatism, and digestive issues. The plant's extracts have also been studied for their potential to reduce stress and improve sleep quality. Additionally, Chrysanthemum fisherae may have antimicrobial properties, which could help protect against infections. Further research is needed to confirm the full extent of its health benefits.", "parts": "Chrysanthemum fisherae is a species of flowering plant, and it is used in traditional Chinese medicine. Chrysanthemum fisherae is used to treat various conditions, including fever, rheumatism, and respiratory problems. The plant's flowers, leaves, and roots are used in medicinal preparations. The flowers are particularly valued for their antipyretic and anti-inflammatory properties. Chrysanthemum fisherae is also used to treat digestive problems and skin conditions.", "intro": "Chrysanthemum fisherae, also known as Yu Xing Cao, is a type of flowering plant that belongs to the family Asteraceae. The plant is valued for its medicinal properties, which include anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant effects, contributing to its potential health benefits such as reducing fever, relieving headaches, and protecting against oxidative stress. The bioactive constituents of Chrysanthemum fisherae include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and sesquiterpenoids, which are responsible for its therapeutic properties. In traditional Chinese medicine, the plant is commonly used to make teas, infusions, and decoctions, as well as being incorporated into capsules and tablets, making it a popular herbal preparation for various health conditions."}